particular, it is as fast as third party LVSR engines.

\section download Obtaining the source code

Juicer is available <a
href="http://www.idiap.ch/software/juicer/sources">here</a>.  It is
released under a BSD license, which is quite permissive.  Further
information is in the README in the distribution.

In order to build juicer, you need these two dependencies:

 - <a href="http://www.torch.ch/">Torch3</a>.  The distribution that
comes with <a href="http://torch3vision.idiap.ch/">Torch3vision</a>
probably works too.
 - <a href="http://www.idiap.ch/software/tracter">Tracter</a>
 .

\section authors Authors

Juicer was originally written by <a
href="http://www.ict.csiro.au/staff/Darren.Moore/">Darren Moore</a>
whilst he was at Idiap, although a significant part of his work was
done under the AMI training program at Sheffield.  Dynamic composition
(on-the-fly) was added by Octavian Cheng (although this is not
currently maintained).  <a href="http://www.idiap.ch/~dines">John
Dines</a> also contributed.

More recently, the package has been overhauled by, and is maintained
by, <a href="http://www.idiap.ch/~pgarner">Phil Garner</a>.  Most of
the HTK compatibility work is by <a
href="http://www.dcs.shef.ac.uk/~vinny">Vinny Wan</a>.  Le Zhang
recently wrote the "Lite" (and fast) decoder core.


